<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is wire ampacity?", answer: "Ampacity is the maximum current a conductor can carry continuously without exceeding its insulation temperature rating. NEC Table 310.16 lists base ampacities for conductors in raceway, cable, or direct-buried at 30 °C ambient. The base value must be adjusted for actual ambient temperature and for the number of current-carrying conductors in the bundle." },
  { question: "What is the ampacity of 12 AWG copper?", answer: "At 75 °C insulation rating (THWN, XHHW) the base ampacity is 25 amps per NEC Table 310.16. At 60 °C (TW) it is 20 amps. At 90 °C (THHN) it is 30 amps. However, NEC 240.4(D)(5) limits the overcurrent protection on 12 AWG to 20 amps maximum — you can not put a 12 AWG wire on a 25 or 30 amp breaker even if the table allows more. The same 14 AWG limit is 15 amps, and 10 AWG is 30 amps." },
  { question: "What is the 60/75/90 C column for?", answer: "The three columns correspond to the insulation temperature rating of the conductor. 60 °C is older TW/UF type. 75 °C includes THWN, XHHW, RHW. 90 °C includes THHN, THHW, THWN-2, and XHHW-2. You must use the lower of: the conductor rating, the termination rating (most residential breakers/receptacles are 75 °C), and any derating factors. Modern THHN/THWN-2 is dual-rated so you can use the 75 °C or 90 °C column depending on terminations." },
  { question: "When do I need to derate for ambient temperature?", answer: "When the ambient air temperature differs from the 30 °C (86 °F) base used in Table 310.16. Hot attics can reach 50-60 °C; the derating factor at 50 °C for 90 °C insulation is 0.82 — meaning a 30 A conductor only carries 24.6 A. Underground conduits below the frost line see 15-20 °C and get an uplift factor of 1.08-1.11. Always derate to the hottest condition the run encounters along its length." },
  { question: "What is bundle derating and when does it apply?", answer: "NEC 310.15(C)(1) requires derating when more than three current-carrying conductors share a raceway or cable. The factors are 80% for 4-6 wires, 70% for 7-9 wires, 50% for 10-20 wires. For example, six 12 AWG THWN wires in one conduit derate from 25 A to 25 × 0.80 = 20 A — the same wire can carry less because the bundle traps heat. Grounding conductors and neutrals on balanced 3-phase circuits do not count in the conductor count." }
]) %>

